shared_text:
United Way of the Lower Eastern Shore
4 hrs ·

Tomorrow, Sunday September 13th is a One Stop Shop Resource Fair, presented by the Lower Shore Vulnerable Populations Task Force!

Stop by United Way of the Lower Eastern Shore, located at 803 N. Salisbury Blvd., in Salisbury, MD., from 1-4 p.m., and check out tons of community organizations providing resources like food, rental assistance, voter registration, Census 2020, masks, hand sanitizer and more.

The event will be held rain or shine. For more information, contact Tri Community Mediation at 410-548-7174 or tcm@tricommuniytmediation.org.

We hope to see you there!

News from the Class of 2021: Congratulations to Parkside High's Sara Sadjadi, who has started her senior year with the news that she has been named a semifinalist in the 2021 National Merit Scholarship Program. The semifinalists in this program are students who show exceptional academic ability and potential for success in rigorous college studies. Way to go, Sara, you make your schools (Parkside High, Bennett Middle, North Salisbury Elementary and Fruitland Primary) very proud!

Parkside High

Wicomico Public Schools Mental Health Awareness
September 10 at 2:08 PM ·

Today is World Suicide Prevention Day. We can save a life by reaching out when you notice the warning signs of suicide. If your student is struggling with depression or anxiety please know that each school has mental health staff available to speak with your student or provide you with resources to seek support from an outside agency. Please know that we are here to help you!

On the last weekday of summer, East Salisbury Elementary welcomed parents and students who drove through the school's parking lot to receive school-issued backpacks for the new school year. Laptop backpacks were purchased for students Prekindergarten-Grade 5 to safely carry and store student laptops and school supplies. This grant-funded purchase of laptop backtops for Prek-Grade 5 students countywide will support students during virtual learning and for the return to school buildings when they need to transport their laptop for use at school.

East Salisbury Elementary

post_text:
MEALS FOR STUDENTS. This Friday will be the last day for summer meal distribution at 9 schools and 8 community sites, but that's because the Food Service program is expanding pickup options starting with the first day of school on Tuesday, Sept. 8.

Meal bundles, with breakfast and lunch, are provided at no charge to all students of Wicomico County Public Schools. Meal bundles will be available every school day at every school. Students and parents/caregivers can pick up meals at any school, regardless of where the student is enrolled.

Middle and high schools will give out meals 8-10 a.m., and elementary schools will distribute meals 11 a.m.-1 p.m. Pittsville Middle and High will hand out meal bundles during both time slots. Two community locations, in Bivalve and Sharptown, will continue to serve students and families.

Superintendent of Schools Dr. Donna C. Hanlin is pleased to announce that the popular Family Portal is open for the 2020-2021 school year for parents and guardians of students, and students themselves, in grades 1-12. All passwords from the previous school year have been reset, for security purposes. Instructions are below for logging in for the 2020-2021 school year.

Family Portal: https://x2.wcboe.org/x2sis/logon.do

Middle and high school student schedules for the new school year are available on the Family Portal. Once logged in, click on the “My Info” top tab and look for the “Current Schedule” side tab. To see all of the student’s classes, click on matrix view and then list view.

More: https://www.wcboe.org/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&DomainID=4&ModuleInstanceID=6939&ViewID=6446EE88-D30C-497E-9316-3F8874B3E108&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=10373&PageID=1

post_text:
Statement from Wicomico County Public Schools:

Wicomico County Public Schools is continuing to prepare for an effective and robust virtual learning program for all students beginning on Sept. 8, following our established Recovery Plan. WCPS is planning to bring small groups of students into our buildings, and we are on track to have some students safely in as early as mid-September.

Wicomico Public Schools will continue to monitor the ongoing health situation and return to in-person instruction, most likely using a hybrid model, as soon as conditions allow.

Thank you to Salisbury University for the generous donation of 30 laptops to Pinehurst Elementary (and another 30 to a school in Baltimore) to support the education of possible future SU Sea Gulls. The laptops will soon be in the hands of Pinehurst students for the 2020-2021 school year.

SU Chief of Staff Eli Modlin delivered the 30 laptops to Pinehurst this morning, and presented them to leaders of Wicomico County Public Schools including Director of Technology Bob Langan, Pinehurst Elementary Principal Kevin Smith, Chief Academic Officer / Assistant Superintendent for Instruction Dr. Frederick L. Briggs, and Pinehurst Elementary Assistant Principal Lisa King.

Read the whole story: https://www.salisbury.edu/news/article/2020-8-21-SU-Donates-60-Laptops-to-Students-in-Wicomico-County-Baltimore-City

If you or someone you know is behind on rent due to COVID-19-related loss of employment, Habitat for Humanity of Wicomico County may be able to help you with up to three months of rental assistance. Applicants must reside within Wicomico County, but outside the Salisbury city limits. Apply online* at www.wicomicohabitat.org, or call
410-546-1551 for more information.

*Applications in Haitian Creole and Spanish are downloadable on the website.

post_text:
Bike donations, Part II: The bicycles donated by Salisbury University Police Department for students of Wicomico County Public Schools to work on through the SHOP (Students Helping Others Pedal) program has made its first delivery! On Friday, WCPS took bikes to the Joseph House in Salisbury, where they were received by Sister Virginia Peckham of the Order Little Sisters of Jesus & Mary and Dave Heninger, Manager of the Joseph House. This delivery of donated bicycles, made by David Harner and Devin Smith on behalf of WCPS, included some adult bikes for men in the Joseph House Workshop program to use as transportation to employment and some children’s bikes for families in need. Other donation deliveries are planned for later this month. Thanks to the Tri-County Council for the Lower Eastern Shore of Maryland for funding, and for everyone at SU and in Wicomico Schools who had a hand in making this program a success.

Salisbury University

Wicomico County Public Schools will start the 2020-2021 school year with virtual learning for the first semester, supporting the health and safety of students, staff and families while providing robust, consistent instruction through online platforms.

Superintendent of School Dr. Donna C. Hanlin presented her recommendation Tuesday, July 28 during a virtual special meeting of the Board of Education. The Board unanimously approved the plan for virtual learning for the fall semester.

post_text: Wicomico County Public Schools and the Wicomico County Board of Education join the entire Wicomico County community in extending sincere condolences to the family and friends of Wicomico County Executive Bob Culver on his passing today. Mr. Culver was a 1970 graduate of Wicomico High School and served his community well in public service, including working with the school system, Board of Education, Wicomico County Council and state officials on the education budget and school building projects. We hold his family in our thoughts and prayers during this difficult time.

post_text:
From Parkside High CTE Horticulture instructor Jerry Kelley:

Congratulations to Horticulture student Anna Smith (Parkside senior), selected as a Maryland Delegate to the Global Youth Institute of the World Food Prize! Anna's nomination research: Yemen: Starving Citizens, Starving World. http://aplusgardencentre.weebly.com/malnutrition-yemen.html

Anna works at Chesterfield Heirlooms in Pittsville, and says that, "Providing access to healthy and nutritious food is important, satisfying and hard work."

Each year, 200 exceptional high school students from across the U.S. and other countries are selected to participate in the Global Youth Institute hosted by the World Food Prize Foundation. We are so impressed with our local Horticulture scholar Anna, and know she will represent her program, school, school system, state and industry very well.

post_text: More than two months ago, Teresa and Bill McCain made the virtual announcement that the winner of the McCain Foundation's 2020 Rising Star Award for second-year teachers was Heather Smith, a Special Education teacher at Wicomico High School. Last week, they finally got to meet her in person to present her with a check for $1,000, a certificate from the Wicomico County Council, and a bat personalized with her name (part of Bill McCain's eagerness to recognize a "rookie of the year.") Congratulations Heather Smith, you represent our early career teachers very well!

Wor-Wic Community College
June 29 at 2:02 PM ·

The Maryland Community College Promise Scholarship program has changed. You could be eligible to attend for free. The service obligation and the age requirement have been eliminated in an effort to offer more students the opportunity to be eligible for up to $5,000 annually to attend a community college. If you listed a four-year institution on your FAFSA or MSFAA, and now plan to attend a community college, you can change your school of choice prior to the deadline of July 31. Full details here: http://ow.ly/eSxW50Akyx8

post_text: A Westside Primary student waves goodbye to WPS staff during the school's summer sendoff parking lot parade June 16.

post_text: Summer sendoff at Westside Intermediate School Tuesday evening. At times the line of vehicles stretched around the corner and up the street beside the school, because so many students and families wanted this chance to say goodbye. Staff members were physically distanced throughout the main parking lot, using empty parking spaces to measure out separation. It was 6:30 p.m. Tuesday by the time this last school sendoff ended, bringing an unofficial end to the 2019-2020 school year.

Staff members were physically distanced throughout the main parking lot, using empty parking spaces to measure out separation. It was 6:30 p.m. Tuesday by the time this last school sendoff ended, bringing an unofficial end to the 2019-2020 school year.

post_text: Summer sendoff Tuesday evening at Westside Primary. Students had been away from school since March 13, and officially off school since June 12. Teachers and other staff members were off the clock at the end of teachers' last day of the 2019-2020. But the scene in front of Westside Primary was festive Tuesday evening, as parents drove their children by a long line of WPS staff on the school sidewalk to say thank you, and goodbye for the summer.

Superintendent of Schools Dr. Donna C. Hanlin, Chief Academic Officer Dr. Frederick Briggs, and the Board of Education are pleased to announce a number of school leadership changes for Wicomico County Public Schools, effective July 1.

These promotions, appointments and transfers reflect adjustments due to retirements as well as the school system’s commitment to providing additional leadership staff to support school safety and student success. With each of these announced changes, Wicomico County Public Schools strives to provide consistent, transformative leadership at the school level.

It wasn’t possible to hold the usual day after celebration at school for the new Wicomico Teacher of the Year, but colleagues of Hemalatha Bhaskaran made sure the day was still very special. Mrs. Bhaskaran stepped out of her house to find her principal, supervisor and James M. Bennett High mascot Clippy waiting at a safe distance with gifts and a Teacher of the Year yard sign. Before long, a parade of honking cars driven by JMB staffers rolled by to shout congratulations and show signs for her. Mrs. Bhaskaran’s joyful tears showed just how much she appreciated the unique Teacher of the Year tribute.

Did you catch the announcement of the 2020-2021 Wicomico Teacher of the Year on DelmarvaLife Thursday? Here it is!

https://youtu.be/VSPNtHsirA0

Earlier today Superintendent of Schools Dr. Donna Hanlin surprised the teachers with the finalist news during a Zoom interview with Lisa Bryant about distance learning. You can watch that interview tonight on DelmarvaLife at 5 p.m. to see the surprise announcement.

Congratulations to:

Primary Finalist: Chelsey Mangum, Prekindergarten 3 Year Olds, Beaver Run Elementary

Intermediate Finalist: Kelly Hamilton, Thinking and Doing (TAD) Program, North Salisbury Elementary

Middle School Finalist: James McCrobie, 6th- to 8th-Grade Social Studies/STEM, Salisbury Middle

High School Finalist: Hemalatha Bhaskaran, Environmental Science, James M. Bennett High

The 2020-2021 Wicomico Teacher of the Year will be named on WBOC's DelmarvaLife at about 5 p.m. Thursday.

Please check out this video to hear what our finalists love about teaching.

Governor Larry Hogan

The distribution of meal bundles for Wicomico children continues this week, with food given out 12-1 p.m. Monday, Wednesday and Friday at numerous school and community locations. That will be the meal bundle distribution schedule through the weeks that school buildings remain closed, which is currently scheduled to be May 15.

The MSDE Division of Early Childhood Development recently launched Wednesday Watch Parties on Facebook that demonstrate short videos, 1 - 3 minutes long, of learning activities families can do at home from math and reading to breathing exercises. The intended audience are families with children, birth - grade 12. The videos will be featured on Facebook Live,@MDEngageEarly every Wednesday at noon.

Become part of the family engagement learning team by uploading your own short video: https://marylandfamiliesengage.org/show-us-your-shorts/

post_text: Our music educators and our students do wonderful work together in our schools, and here's just one piece of proof: Wicomico County Public Schools has once again been named one of the Best Communities for Music Education by the NAMM Foundation, for the 14th time and 11th straight year! Congratulations to all of those involved in outstanding music education in our schools through music classes and other musical opportunities. And thanks to all who support music education in our schools.

Wicomico County Public Schools
April 6 at 8:38 AM ·

Distribution of meal bundles for children takes place 3 days a week from 12-1 p.m. at 18 locations around Wicomico County. Meal bundles are given out for any child up to age 18 and any WCPS student 18 or older with physical or mental disabilities.

Starting this week, meal bundles will be larger on some days to cover two days of food at a time. This week's pickup days are Monday, Tuesday and Thursday. Next week's pickup days are Tuesday, Thursday and Friday.

Parents! With all that has happened the past few weeks, we wanted to remind you to complete the 2020 CENSUS! This will help determine funding or our schools over the next 10 Years! It will certainly help us if EVERYONE completes it by going online, calling or mailing in the Census you received in the mail.

Simply open the form and follow the instructions. Again, it only takes 10 Minutes of your time! THIS IS SO IMPORTANT for our schools and community!

Make yourself and your family COUNT. Complete the 2020 Census Today!

#2020CensusMaryland

Wicomico County Public Schools added 38 new photos.
April 6 at 3:44 PM ·

When the state closed schools after March 13th, the March 14th concert by the first Wicomico ACES (All-County Elementary School) Choir had to be called off. But before that happened, these 4th- and 5th-grade students from throughout Wicomico Schools had worked hard on a wonderful program, under the direction of music teachers Victoria Oberdick, Dr. Nan Richerson and John Wixted. We thought the students' teachers, friends and families would enjoy seeing these happy faces again, in these photos taken during rehearsal on March 4th. Thanks once again to the Community Foundation of the Eastern Shore for its support of the ACES Choir.

post_text: Wicomico Schools is proud to support Peninsula Regional Medical Center as it leads the effort to keep our community healthy in these troubling times. The school system was also able to donate light fixtures for the hospital's use. We look forward to continuing to partner with PRMC in better days.
shared_text:
TidalHealth Peninsula Regional
April 1 at 9:33 AM ·

As many of you know, the COVID-19 situation forced us to cancel our 2020 HealthFest health fair that was scheduled for March 28 at James M. Bennett High School in Salisbury.

Our partner in that event, each year, is the Wicomico County Board of Education (WCBOE).

Today, they stopped by the Medical Center with a donation of gloves, masks, temperature scanners, eyewear and hand sanitizer. Our partnership is stronger than ever and we look forward to teaming up with the Board, again, in 2021 for HealthFest.

Thank you to our friends at the WCBOE and to everyone in our community who has donated to Team PRMC.

MEALS FOR CHILDREN DURING CLOSURE OF SCHOOLS: SCHOOL AND COMMUNITY SITES

Wicomico County Public Schools is making meal bundle pickup available for all children weekdays from 12-1 p.m. at numerous school and community sites. Meal bundles (lunch/supper/breakfast) are available to all children up to age 18, and to students over 18 who are mentally or physically disabled.

Schools:

-Delmar Elementary
-East Salisbury Elementary
-Fruitland Primary
-Pemberton Elementary
-Pinehurst Elementary
-Prince Street Elementary
-Salisbury Middle
-Pittsville Elementary and Middle
-Willards Elementary

Community sites for WCPS meals:

-Allen Community Hall
-Asbury United Methodist Church (Sharptown)
-Christian Shelter
-Nelsons United Methodist Church/Epoch Dream Center (Hebron)
-Newton Community Center
-Renovate Church (Delmar)
-Stone Grove Crossing Community Center
-Westside Volunteer Fire Department (Bivalve)

More pickup sites may be added. For more information, please refer to our website at www.wcboe.org, or send inquiries to comments@wcboe.org

post_text: The deputies with the Wicomico County Sheriff's Office who serve Wicomico County Public Schools as School Resource Officers are an invaluable, proactive part of the school team for our students and staff. What does it mean to them to serve in schools and in the community? Find out as former James M. Bennett High SRO DFC Dave Goldberg answers his final dispatch call today.
shared_text:
Wicomico County Sheriff's Office
March 19 at 12:35 PM ·

The Wicomico County Sheriff’s Office would like to congratulate Deputy First Class Dave Goldberg on his retirement after 13 years of service to the citizens of Wicomico County.

Prior to his employment with the Sheriff’s Office he was a child protective services investigator and worked for the Department of Social Services at the Wicomico County Child Advocacy Center before he realized his dream of becoming a Sheriff’s Deputy.

During his tenure with the Sheriff’s Office, Deputy First Class Dave Goldberg worked as a school resource officer at James M Bennett High School and later as a deputy in our civil division.

The Wicomico County Sheriff’s Office would like to thank Deputy First Class Dave Goldberg for his dedicated service to the law enforcement profession and we wish him the best of luck in his future endeavors.

Your student's school is also a great source of information for students and families about learning activities and online instructional tools, many of which were already in use before the closure. post_text:
MEALS FROM SCHOOLS DURING CLOSURE

Starting Tuesday, Wicomico County Public Schools will serve free nutritious meals to children and teens during the two-week mandatory closure of schools. The meals will be available to all children up to age 18, and to students over 18 who are mentally or physically disabled.

Meal pickup will begin on Tuesday, March 17 at six school locations, and will continue each weekday through Friday, March 27th. A lunch and a snack will be available for pickup from 12-1 p.m. at an outside area at the following school locations:

• East Salisbury Elementary
• Fruitland Primary
• Pemberton Elementary
• Pinehurst Elementary
• Prince Street Elementary
• Salisbury Middle

For more information, please refer to our website at www.wcboe.org, or send inquiries to comments@wcboe.org

Today I announced a series of major actions to protect public health and safety and limit the spread of the COVID-19 pandemic in Maryland. A comprehensive list can be found here: https://governor.maryland.gov/2020/03/12/governor-hogan-announces-major-actions-to-protect-public-health-limit-spread-of-covid-19-pandemic/

Our state has already faced and overcome daunting challenges before, and we will do so again.

When a student says, “This is the best day of my life”, there is not a better feeling for teachers and a school.

On Wednesday at Fruitland Primary School, half the students were working on a "Be Kind coloring contest", with the winner getting to have lunch and ice cream with Ms. Johanning!

The other half were working on their "Be Kind" Crown. While they were working the students talked about "What is kindness, how can you be kind, and how does it make you feel when people are kind to you."

post_text:
Wicomico Public Schools Extra Mile Award winners for the month of February were recognized on Tuesday at the monthly Board of Education meeting.

Congratulations to Courtney Coco, an Orchestra Teacher at both Mardela Middle and Salisbury Middle Schools. She organized a Prom Dress Drive that netted over 200 dresses for the coming upcoming prom season, and girls will be able to buy a Prom Dress for $30 or less.

She was accompanied by Mardela Dean of Students Cameron Ball, and pictured with Supt. Dr. Donna Hanlin and Board Chairman Don Fitzgerald.

The other Extra Mile winner was Tyrone Suggs, the Assistant Building Service Manager at Delmar Elementary School. Mr. Suggs goes above and beyond with a great smile, positive attitude, and if you need anything at all done, simply "Ask Tyrone."

Mr. Suggs is accompanied by Delmar Principal Kirby Bryson, and pictured with Supt. Dr. Hanlin and Board Chairman Don Fitzgerald.

Congratulations and THANKS to Ms. Coco and Mr. Suggs on going the Extra Mile for Wicomico County Public Schools!

shared_text:
Parkside High School Wrestling
March 10 at 4:12 PM ·

“Once a Gator, always a Gator”
These two Parkside studs and products of Glen Avenue Elementary School (Gators) were invited back to their roots today to walk the halls of Glen Ave Elem, talk to their former teachers and meet with current students to inspire them and teach them the value of hard work, dedication, perseverance, and commitment to accomplish their goals. Pictured below are Big Mike Collins (left) and Alijah Bivans (right) who have certainly accomplished a lot since their days as a Glen Ave Elem Gator.

Big Mike: 2019 Bayside Conference 1st team OL and 2nd team DL selection in football, 2020 Bayside Champ, 1A/2A East Regional Champ, and MPSSAA State Champ in wrestling. Attending Shepherd Univ next fall.

Alijah Bivans: 2019 Bayside Conference 1st team LB, 2nd team RB, and DelmarvaNow Player of the Year in football and MPSSAA state 5th place winner in wrestling.

Proud of these guys for being role models for the future Parkside Rams who will be coming from Glen Ave Elementary!
Laura Heath Becker
Glen Avenue Elementary

Wicomico's first All-County Orchestra is in rehearsals all day today (Friday, March 6), and will perform a concert at 7 tonight in the Wicomico High Auditorium. The All-County Orchestra is under the direction of collegiate orchestra conductor Dr. Peter Isaacson. Participants were selected by audition from Wicomico's middle and high schools, and all middle and high schools will have representatives on the stage. Tickets are $4 at the door, and all proceeds will support the next All-County Orchestra in 2021. Wicomico's orchestra teachers and students appreciate the support of the Community Foundation of the Eastern Shore, which provided a grant for the launch of the All-County Orchestra.

post_text:
You'll see many employees of Wicomico County Public Schools dressed casual today in support of young readers. Today's casual day proceeds will help the United Way of the Lower Eastern Shore continue to grow its participation in Dolly Parton's Imagination Library, which mails a book a month to every child under age 5 who is registered for the program. Our staff donations, and donations from other Lower Shore county school systems that have taken up the fundraising for early literacy challenge from Wicomico Superintendent of Schools Dr. Donna Hanlin, will help young children and parents share the love of reading, which is fundamental to success in school.

The United Way of the Lower Eastern Shore has information on its website about the Imagination Library, and a form to register a child: https://www.uwles.org/imaginationlibrary

Learn more about the history and impact of the Imagination Library in an upcoming documentary.

The Eastern Shore Literacy Association (ESLA) filled Holloway Hall Auditorium at Salisbury University the evening of Wednesday, March 4 to announce the 2020 Young Authors’ Contest winners. With more than 200 entries encompassing public, private, and homeschooled students on the Shore’s lower three counties, the contest continues to become more and more competitive as the quality of writing reaches ever higher levels. Congratulations to all the finalists!

The 1st Place winners in each grade level and category were forwarded onto the state level competition hosted by the State of Maryland Literacy Association. The Lower Shore had three students garner a 1st or 2nd place ranking in the state Young Authors’ Contest:

Jenny Chen, James M. Bennett High, Grade 11 Short Story – 1st Place
Emily Garlock, James M. Bennett High, Grade 9 Poetry – 2nd Place
Maya Matava, James M. Bennett High, Grade 10 Poetry – 2nd Place

In a battle of crosstown rivals in the Class 2A Basketball playoffs, Wi-Hi defeated Parkside 74 - 60 on Tuesday to advance to the Regional Championship game. It was a tight first half with the Tribe holding a slim 35 - 28 lead at the break.

Both teams seemed a little nervous with a lot of turnovers and missed layups, but in the end Wi-Hi picked up the win to advance in the Boys Playoffs.

The Tribe will host North Caroline on Thursday for the Regional Championship. Coach Waller will certainly remind his team that two years ago the Bulldogs came in as heavy underdogs, and upset a previously unbeaten Wi-Hi team.

Enjoy these photos from the Parkside vs Wi-Hi playoff matchup.

Good season Rams, and now Good Luck Wi-Hi in the Regional Final on Thursday at home!

post_text: Congratulations to the JMB Wrestling team on its success at Regionals. Best of luck to the five wrestlers going on to States!
shared_text:
James M. Bennett Wrestling
February 29 at 10:55 PM ·

The day started out at 7am the team left the hotel, all with goals of their own hoping to fulfill them by the end of the day. The reward, another week of practice, another week of weight management, but ultimately a trip to the big show.

Bennett Wrestlers set out to complete this task and unfortunately 2 fell short. With their heads held high they supported their teammates the rest of the way.

For the first time since 2005 James M. Bennett will be sending 5 Wrestlers to the State Tournament!! I’m am so incredibly proud of these athletes. They fought so hard today and it paid off.

Join me in congratulating the following Clippers on their accomplishments. The State qualifiers are,

Regional Champions:

Senior Julia Fitzpatrick
(Becomes the first Girl in JMB School history to win a Regional Title in wrestling)

Junior Micah Reddish - Still undefeated on the season 43-0

Junior Eric Ward - knocked off the #2 Ranked guy in the state in the finals!

Regional Runner-Up:

Senior Troy Gibson

Regional 4th place:

Freshman Brian Kintzer

post_text: Learn more about this outstanding musician and music educator at Wicomico High and the Visual and Performing Arts Program.
shared_text:
City of Salisbury, Maryland
February 29 at 2:00 PM ·

Today to close out our #blackhistorymonth series, we're featuring two amazing members of our community! First, meet local musician, composer, and music educator/choral director with Wicomico County Public Schools, Stephen P. Harvey. Read our interview with Stephen below 👇

SBY: You’re an accomplished musician and educator, is there an African American artist that has had a significant impact on you, your creative process and your teaching and directing?

Stephen: I couldn’t name it down to one artist. Since we don’t exist in a vacuum there’s a litany of black (is say that because not all are American) artists that have influenced my musical palette, my educational process, and goals in the profession of music. However, if I had to pick a list of African American artists, I would have to choose Billy Strayhorn, Miles Davis, John Coltrane, Wayne Shorter, Dexter Gordon, Langston Hughes, Dudley Randall, and Kendrick Lamar.

Read the rest of our interview with Stephen here: http://bit.ly/SBYstephen
